title: Lead Data Analyst/Data Engineer Team Lead ‚Äì Ozon
post_text: It seems that the peak of the hype about the current version of chatGPT is over. And before OpenAI rolls out the next release, which in addition to text, seems to be able to do pictures and video, I want to voice a thought about the expectations of large language models. Someone finds a lot of the most unexpected applications for them, and someone says "chatGPT is a useless dumbass, doesn't know basic things, can't solve logical problems". But if you take what chatGPT can do as the part of the human brain that is responsible for speech, then chatGPT is already doing just fine. You don't have to expect outstanding abilities in logic, factual knowledge, mathematics, spatial orientation, etc.  As I see it, in solving the problem of creating general artificial intelligence, some chatGPT analogue will act as a convenient speech interface between humans, and more specialized things - "skills", like a notional Matlab, a data warehouse or home robot. Its task is to maintain the dialogue, translating from human to internal language of the respective skill, and vice versa.

post_text: Imagine if you could tell a ML model "play a funk bassline with a jazzy saxophone" and it would synthesize artificial music! Well actually, you don't need to imagine, you can just use it! Introducing RIFFUSION, a Stable Diffusion model trained on Spectrogram image data: https://lnkd.in/ge9_VE6t. The idea is simplistic: - just pick a pre-trained Stable Diffusion model (https://lnkd.in/dpFheWYS)- Take lot of musics with their text descriptions and convert that into Spectrogram image data- Fine-tune to the Stable Diffusion model=> you now have a model that can predict new spectrograms based on other spectrograms or text prompts. Just convert those spectrograms back to musics.¬† If you want more details on how to do it yourself you can follow the process here: https://lnkd.in/gpj_K-UF. I discovered this website yesterday through Alpha Signal's weekly summary: https://alphasignal.ai/. If you to learn more about stable diffusion, you can read my LinkedIn post on it: https://lnkd.in/gxBiU9fB---Follow me on Twitter: https://lnkd.in/eQ454QHD#machinelearning #datascience #stablediffusion

title: –í–µ–¥—É—â–∏–π BI –ê–Ω–∞–ª–∏—Ç–∏–∫ - Tableau Certified Data Analyst
post_text: Last summer Tableau has announced a new Certified Tableau Data Analyst exam instead of a well-known Desktop Associate. And this is a story when I couldn't resist, and I needed to know what's insideIn a nutshell:- Three isolated sections, you should complete them one by one - can't double-check the responses once you complete the section- No more Internet, official knowledge base is available in the lab part only (as .pdf - but it is actually not needed there)- Rather easy hands-on lab - e.g. how to create a histogram, how to create a conditional set with TOP N- Tableau Desktop is not available in the first and third knowledge-based sections, so you can't practically check your suggestion - you need to recall syntax and the sequence of stepsWhat to pay attention to when preparing:- Calculations (types, syntax, applicability, you may be asked to select between TOTAL() and WINDOW_SUM())- Formatting - what actions should be sequentially applied to get the screen you see- Practice - check the Exam guide and practice everything that sounds unfamiliar to you More details are here (in Russian):https://lnkd.in/eS-5Cyx9and here:https://t.me/datanature#tableau #tableaucertified #data #businessintellegence
